{"accepted":[{"assertion":"AI-contributions wiki claim — wiki: Full solution.","id":"vf_089c8e817681b266","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #987: declared status 'proved'. Formalized: no. Let $x_1,x_2,\\ldots \\in (0,1)$ be an infinite sequence and let\\[A_k=\\limsup_{n\\to \\infty}\\left\\lvert \\sum_{j\\leq n} e(kx_j)\\right\\rvert,\\]where $e(x)=e^{2\\pi ix}$.\n\nIs it true that\\[\\limsup_{k\\to \\infty} A_k=\\infty?\\]Is it possible for $A_k=o(k)$? Current best: Erd\\H{o}s \\cite{Er64b} remarks it is 'easy to see' that\\[\\limsup_{k\\to \\infty}\\left(\\sup_n\\left\\lvert \\sum_{j\\leq n} e(kx_j)\\right\\rvert\\right)=\\infty.\\]Erd\\H{o}s \\cite{Er65b} later found a 'very easy' proof that $A_k\\gg \\log k$ for infinitely many $k$. Clunie \\cite{Cl67} proved that $A_k\\gg k^{1/2}$ infinitely often, and that there exist sequences with $A_k\\leq k$ for all $k$. Tao has independently found a proof that $A_k\\gg k^{1/2}$ infinitely often (see the comment section). Liu \\cite{Li69} showed that, for any $\\epsilon>0$, $A_k\\gg k^{1-\\epsilon}$ infinitely often, under the additional assumption that there are only a finite number of distinct points. Prize: no. Tags: analysis, discrepancy.","id":"vf_285881bba6f1b7fd","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: FC 987 (PR #4354) [in-pr] https://github.com/google-deepmind/formal-conjectures/pull/4354.","id":"vf_f77504e096a1c94b","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[{"accepted":false,"claim":"Pinned Formal Conjectures activity classification; integration activity does not establish mathematical truth.","id":"activity:fc-statement_edit:987","kind":"statement_edit","lifecycle":"banked","source_ref":"sources/formal-conjectures-activity.yaml#problem-987","trust":"declared"}],"activity_types":["statement_edit"],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[{"commit":"8f6648ff0fbd771db53859cd436d37a8d6a68a57",